{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The conversation history passed to the LLM is trimmed to the most recent 10 messages when the full history exceeds the context window.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure boundary is module handoff: trimming logic must be reflected in the actual payload sent to the LLM client. Unit was rejected because behavior text says \"passed to the LLM\" (not just local list slicing). System was rejected because no real OS/network/subprocess behavior is required; an in-process fake LLM client can expose payload mistakes. Agentic/Workflow were rejected because correctness does not depend on model output quality or multi-step model decisions.","test_description":"Wire request handler + history manager + LLM client adapter with a fake in-process LLM transport that records request payload. Provide >10 prior messages, invoke generation, and assert exactly the latest 10 messages are sent in order. Also assert no older message IDs appear in payload.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Test requires cross-module wiring (history -> request builder -> LLM adapter), so Integration is necessary and sufficient.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.35,"Integration":0.6,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The generated response addresses the customer's question rather than producing a generic or off-topic reply.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"This is output-quality validation of real model behavior; deterministic stubs would hide failures (deterministic-assertion trap). Integration was considered and rejected because it can only verify routing/payload, not whether response is actually on-topic. Workflow was rejected because behavior text is about a single generated reply, not a required multi-step agent pipeline.","test_description":"Run prompts against the real production model/config on a labeled set of customer questions with relevance rubric (or human-validated